<p class="guide-intro">"Ideal body weight" is one of the most searched health questions — but the answer depends on which formula you use, and all four major formulas give slightly different results. This guide explains each formula, shows you the numbers by height and sex, and explains the important limitations of weight-based targets.</p>

<h2>The 4 Main Ideal Weight Formulas</h2>
<p>All four formulas below use <strong>height</strong> and <strong>sex</strong> as inputs. They were developed between 1964 and 1983, primarily for clinical use in medication dosing:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Formula</th><th>Year</th><th>Men (base + per inch)</th><th>Women (base + per inch)</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Devine</strong></td><td>1974</td><td>50 kg + 2.3 kg/in</td><td>45.5 kg + 2.3 kg/in</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Robinson</strong></td><td>1983</td><td>52 kg + 1.9 kg/in</td><td>49 kg + 1.7 kg/in</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Miller</strong></td><td>1983</td><td>56.2 kg + 1.41 kg/in</td><td>53.1 kg + 1.36 kg/in</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Hamwi</strong></td><td>1964</td><td>48 kg + 2.7 kg/in</td><td>45.4 kg + 2.3 kg/in</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p style="font-size:13px;color:#6b7280;margin-top:8px">All formulas apply per inch above 5 feet (60 inches / 152 cm).</p>

