<h2>Why the Formulas Disagree</h2>
<p>The spread between formulas can be 5–10 kg for the same person. This reflects genuine disagreement among researchers about what "ideal" means and how to model it. Key reasons for divergence:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Different base weights</strong> — Hamwi uses 48 kg for men at 5', Miller uses 56.2 kg</li>
  <li><strong>Different per-inch increments</strong> — Devine adds 2.3 kg/inch, Miller only 1.41 kg/inch</li>
  <li><strong>Different reference populations</strong> — each was derived from different actuarial or clinical datasets</li>
  <li><strong>No adjustment for body composition</strong> — a muscular 6'0" man and a sedentary 6'0" man get the same IBW</li>
</ul>

<h2>Limitations of Ideal Body Weight</h2>
<p>IBW formulas were designed for <strong>clinical pharmacology</strong> — specifically to calculate drug doses for obese patients where actual body weight would cause overdosing. They were never intended as personal fitness targets or aesthetics goals. Key limitations:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Do not account for <strong>muscle mass</strong> — athletes often exceed IBW by 10–20%</li>
  <li>Do not adjust for <strong>age</strong> — older adults naturally lose muscle, so IBW may be unrealistically low</li>
  <li>Do not account for <strong>frame size</strong> (small, medium, large bone structure)</li>
  <li>Derived from predominantly <strong>white European</strong> populations — less validated for other ethnicities</li>
  <li>Produce results <strong>below WHO healthy BMI range</strong> for many tall individuals</li>
</ul>
<p>For a more complete picture, combine IBW with <strong>body fat percentage</strong> and <strong>waist circumference</strong> measurements.</p>

